  "prompt": "What is the difference between Shall and Will?",
  "response": "\"Shall\" and \"will\" are both modal verbs used to indicate future actions, but they have different traditional uses, particularly in British English. Over time, their usage has evolved, and the distinctions between them have become less strict, especially in American English. Here are the traditional differences:\n\n1. **Tradition and Formality**:\n   - **Shall**: Traditionally used with the first person pronouns \"I\" and \"we\" to express future actions. It is more formal and is often found in legal or formal documents. Example: \"I shall attend the meeting.\"\n   - **Will**: Traditionally used with second and third person pronouns \"you,\" \"he,\" \"she,\" \"it,\" \"they\" to indicate future actions. Example: \"He will attend the meeting.\"\n\n2. **Determination and Promise**:\n   - **Shall**: Can be used with second and third person pronouns to express a command, promise, or determination. Example: \"You shall have the opportunity to speak.\"\n   - **Will**: Can indicate intention or willingness, particularly with the first person. Example: \"I will help you with that.\"\n\n3. **Modern Usage**:\n   - In contemporary English, particularly American English, \"will\" is predominantly used for all subjects, and \"shall\" is rarely used in everyday conversation. \"Shall\" may still be encountered in legal contexts or formal writing.\n\n4. **Questions and Offers**:\n   - **Shall**: Often used in questions and offers, especially in British English. Example: \"Shall we go to the park?\" or \"Shall I open the window?\"\n\nOverall, while the traditional rules still apply in certain formal settings, in everyday English, especially in the United States, \"will\" is often used interchangeably for all pronouns, with \"shall\" being used sparingly.",
